  "overall_strengths": [
    "Good coverage of Android manifest/configuration and platform-specific best-practice issues that are easy to miss in generic SAST tools.",
    "Evidence is concrete: SPECK usually reports the exact source/XML snippet plus a line number lookup.",
    "Can analyze both source trees and APKs because it decompiles APKs with JADX first.",
    "Rule 3 is stronger than a pure grep rule because it uses external permission-to-API/content-provider maps.",
    "Optional FlowDroid refinement gives a limited but real whole-app data-flow backstop for selected rules."
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "The default engine is string-based and heuristic. It has no AST, alias analysis, path sensitivity, or symbolic reasoning.",
    "Java only: the main parser scans `.java` files, so Kotlin coverage depends entirely on JADX decompilation quality.",
    "Many rules are proxies for secure coding guidance, not semantic vulnerability proofs.",
    "Several implementations are weak or inconsistent:",
    "Rule 11 claims to check both cache APIs in the comment, but only searches `getExternalCacheDir()`.",
    "Rule 13 \"Check validity of data\" does not actually verify integrity; it only checks whether certain file-input APIs appear in the same scope.",
    "Rule 16's SQL-injection heuristic is questionable: the code comments describe a whitelist of `query`, `update`, `delete`, but the implementation flags `query(...)` itself.",
    "Rule numbering is inconsistent in output after Rule 12. Example: `Rule13` displays/stores as `14`, and `Rule31` displays/stores as `32`.",
    "Rule 8 is especially inconsistent: class name and title say Rule 8, but it calls `self.store(11, ...)`.",
    "FlowDroid coverage is partial:",
    "Active: rules 1, 7, 15, 17, 21, 24, 25, 29",
    "Present but not active: Rule 9 handler is commented out in the dispatch list",
    "Orphaned on disk: Rule 13 FlowDroid artifacts exist but are not imported into the dispatcher",
    "Dependency hygiene is weak: the repo does not ship a dependency manifest for `bs4` / `pymongo`, and a local run in this environment failed immediately because `bs4` was missing.",
    "Taint relevance:",
    "Low.",
    "SPECK is primarily a rule-based syntax/configuration checker.",
    "FlowDroid adds some source/sink reasoning for a minority of rules, but taint analysis is not the core abstraction of the tool and does not dominate coverage."
  ],
